< rating>
4</rating>
<review>The problem with this place is how damn unappetizing "Slim & Healthy Dr Robbin" sounds.  The first time we drove by (over a year ago), we were confused.  Is this a health food/vitamin store?  Are they doing colonics inside?  WTH!?  Not helping the cause is the large signage saying "NO butter, NO sugar, NO msg, etc."  Translate: NO flavor, NO fun, NO WAY!

This is a case of not judging a book by its cover, or in this case, a storefront by its crazy healthy promotional wording.  I was very pleasantly surprised, but perhaps because I expected everything here to taste like cardboard and be made of sprouts.

A surprising menu of pastas, pizzas, and rice and lots of coffees, drinks and desserts.  I ordered the Kimchi & Fish-Roe Tomato Sauce Pasta (whole wheat pasta + bacon, kimchi, onion, garlic, mushroom, bell pepper, red pepper, pepper powder, parmesan, parsley) and was happy with what I'd ordered!  Now, I know this place is supposed to be "healthy" but it's not totally guilt-free.  A portion large enough so I only ate half when I was at the restaurant and then I finished up the rest after I got home a few hours later.

I also loved the complimentary bread and tapenade and next time, I'm going to go for the sugar free gelatos they have in the spinning display.

Yes, there will be a next time!<//review><Pics>None< /Pics>< Response>
None< /Response>

< Text>
This garden is amazing‚Äîso much nature nestled in downtown San Mateo, and this takes the cake. There‚Äôs a lot of greenery, quite a few fish, turtles, a pagoda, and a gazebo from where one can silently take in the garden.

I went there on a busy weekend, so the place was crowded. I recommend going there on a weekday when it‚Äôs quieter and you can wander in solitude, if you‚Äôre seeking solitude, that is.

I‚Äôll be back here again soon.<//Text>

< review>
The Japanese garden is small but beautiful. Well maintained with artistic details everywhere. The pond is home to duck families and several large koi fish of various colors. There are a couple waterfalls and water features as well as a cute bridge and two additional tiny bridges. Stroller parking is just inside the entrance.<//review>

< text>
Lovely garden to visit. The Japanese garden offers free entrance and is best to visit at the beginning of the week. The garden has some beautiful bonsai and Japanese maple trees, both blood maples and green leaf. The garden is small, but very tranquil and pleasant. The garden is located in the middle of Central Park. My family and dog love visiting Central Park, however,  Central Park Japanese garden is off limits to pets.<//text>

< review>
A beautiful Japanese garden, conveniently located
in San Mateo's downtown Central park. Relax and enjoy the flowing
water, Japanese maple trees, and other beautiful plants.

It's also a symbol of San Mateo's Japanese influenced
heritage, along with the Japanese supermarkets.

Hope to see it well maintained and beautiful for many
generations to enjoy.</review>

< user>
116512594249013433675< /user>
< Review>
The Japanese Gardens in San Mateo is quite charming. First parking can seem to be a bit difficult for the out of towner, as the huge Central Park, in which the Japanese Gardens is contained, can be quite busy. That said, park under the tennis courts on East 5th. If you miss it the first time, just lap the block and try again, I know I have has to do that! Once under the tennis courts, you will find shaded easy parking. It may take a minute for you eyes to adjust in the parking lot as it is not brightly lit, but lit enough after a minute of adjustment. The machine for the parking fee is on the end by the entrance and I found the price quite reasonable.  Now exit at the far inside of the lot and presto you are right at the entrance to the Japanese Gardens. The beautiful coy pond is loaded with huge fish! The walk around is so pleasant and it just seems so cool and peaceful as one stroll. Bring a great friend for some wonderful chats, or come alone and let it be reflective and meditative. What ever you choose. This place is so clean, peaceful, well maintained and lovely, I want to come again and again and again ‚Ä¶.</Review>

<user>108453675463629554167<//user>< name>
Karen V Chin</name>
< time>
1431578159959<//time>
<Rate>5< /Rate><text>This Japanese Tea Garden is one of the best kept secrets in San Mateo. Tucked inside a section of the main urban, city park called Central Park, the San Mateo Japanese Garden is free to the public and can be crowded during the weekend with so many people walking, sitting and enjoying the tranquil scenery. For those who are planning to have a party or a wedding, the city of San Mateo will rent this lovely Japanese garden for a fee.

The almost 50 year old San Mateo Japanese Garden was designed by landscape architect, Nagao Sakurai, of the Imperial Palace of Tokyo. This strolling garden features a granite pagoda, tea house, koi pond, waterfall, bamboo grove, walking bridges and many bonsai to admire at every corner. This Japanese Tea Garden is beautiful throughout the year, especially during the late Winter and early Spring when the cherry blossoms are in bloom.

It takes about 10 minutes to walk leisurely the entire perimeter to gaze and enjoy every vista. You can watch the park staff feed the koi at 11:00 a.m. and 3:00 p.m., Monday through Friday, during Spring and Summer (fish are not fed during public hours November - February).

Metered street parking Monday - Saturday. Free parking Sunday.<//text><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< resp>
None</resp>

< username>
Janneta T< /username>
< Text>
Beware of Gabriel Travel! They booked our flight on two separate tickets without informing us about it and it caused so much stress and almost led to $1,000 in lost flights.

Here's what happened.

1. MISINFORMATION. We were booking a flight to Russia. Our travel agent M. sent us a potential itinerary with a tight connection, which we were a bit concerned about, so we asked M. what would happen if any of our flights were delayed, and M. assured us that it would be okay, as it was the responsibility of the airline to rebook us on the next available flight. Satisfied with his answer, we spent an extra $200 to book the flight directly with him rather than doing it ourselves because we wanted the peace of mind that comes with a single-itinerary booking.

2. AGGRESSIVE BEHAVIOR. What a mistake trusting M would be. What happened later was this: the flight for the first part of the journey was delayed, and so we weren't going to make it to our final flight, which was under another itinerary and therefore NOT the responsibility of the airline to rebook. After I finally managed to reach M. to change the last flight, he was very aggressive as soon as I explained the situation. He interrupted me to explain "his side" and at one point I thought he would just hang up on me.

3. LYING. He claimed it was not his problem because he had warned us the flight was on two separate tickets. This is totally false. Both my mom and I were on the phone during the booking process, and at no point did he mention separate tickets to either of us. I've traveled to over 30 different countries and am a seasoned traveler, so I would NEVER have agreed to a booking of two separate tickets when one of the layovers was just 1 hour.

3. POOR JUDGMENT. When people book with travel agents, they rely on the agent to make good judgment calls about itineraries, and this did not happen here. In fact, M. should have done his research and he should never have even offered the itinerary he gave us. Here's why. The itinerary he created had a 1-hour connection in Amsterdam. If we didn't make it on that connection, a simple flight search shows that the next available flight would have been too late in the day for us to make it to the last leg of our trip. And while we didn't know this, he DID know that last leg was on a separate ticket. Essentially, $1,000 worth of tickets for the second part of the trip hinged on making that 1-hour layover. Would an experienced travel agent ever recommend a client such a risky ticket in the first place?

We called a few different travel agents and none could match the price Gabriel Travel did, and now we know why -- because M. gave us a very risky itinerary that the other agencies were too honest to offer. When I contacted the owner of the agency to explain the situation, he was apologetic about his employee's rude behavior and he discounted $60 off of our change fees. He listened carefully to the whole situation and followed up with me via phone. Unfortunately, he was not apologetic about the tickets, the stress it caused us, nor did he acknowledge his employee's incompetence. Instead, he claimed that we all experience stress in our lives and this is just something we have to deal with (and that it wasn't as bad as it could have been, eh?).

Don't make the same expensive mistake we did -- find a travel agent who makes smart, sound itineraries that you can trust so you can start and end your trip stress-free.<//Text>

< Text>
I had a scare recently with my 18 year old Katrina rescue dog when she boated severely after eating. I read about a condition in dogs that quickly leads to shock and death when this occurs so immediately called Solano-Napa Pet Emergency Clinic in Cordelia and  packed her into the car on a Sunday.

The veterinarian was amazing and immediately took her back, created a treatment plan and consulted with me about the risks of various approaches for my 18 year old. She even discussed euthanasia in a very professional and empathic way which I appreciated.

I decided to run the diagnostics and get her treated with a needle that removes the excess gas from her abdominal cavity.

She spent some time at the vet and I picked her up 12 hours later. I must say that I had to be assertive with the registration staff upon discharge because they were so busy.

Great experience overall and I would highly recommend and am grateful for this emergency clinic.< /Text>

< text>
Do everything possible to NOT take your pet here. Checked in at noon Saturday with my cat that had an infected wound & was not even evaluated by a doctor until after midnight. It was 4:00 am Sunday morning before I could pick up my animal. Went through three shifts of employees in that time, each round with at least one a$$hole front desk receptionist. No communication from staff EVER, never got to see a Veterinarian. They have each phase of care broken down into a separate "line": first wait is to be assessed by a Tech, another wait for true assessment by the Vet, another wait to pay for what the Vet recommends, another wait to actually have services provided AFTER you pay, and the final wait to retrieve your pet. No wonder it took 16 hours!!! Terrible process for a business that's supposed to be specialized in FAST emergency services. I will drive past this place 10x over before I ever go back. My first visit is my last.<//text>

< Text>
As with any visit to an emergency vet, this one was a hard one. My 110lb pup had recently been diagnosed with Epilepsy. Only having had 2 episodes prior over the last 3 weeks, I was in shock and completely exhausted after he had 2 in the morning and my vet earlier had said take him to the emergency vet if he has another. That evening the third and most violent seizure happened. I packed him up and hauled him off, expecting to sit there for hours. They pulled us in almost immediately, got him on an IV, and with in an hour they made the recommendation to keep him over night. Reluctantly, I agreed. <response>{'time': 1593739587772, 'text': "First off, I would like to say how sorry we are that you and your family had to go through this traumatic experience. When any pet comes in for trouble breathing, it is by far one of the scariest moments a pet parent can go through. I speak for myself and my team. We all love our pets and have been through these scary moments too. Emergencies can be expensive, especially when a life is on the line. It is true that emergency hospitals are more expensive than a standard daytime practice. We offer special services that do cost our hospital more, like overnight staff and overnight doctors. We need to be prepared for every emergency and that means knowing answers right away. This requires us to have lab equipment in the hospital for immediate answers and multiple oxygen cages for a pet like yours who has trouble breathing. It can be costly, but in comparison to 24 hour facilities in our area, we do try to maintain very competitive prices, which are often more affordable than other emergency clinics. Our doctors make recommendations based on the presentation of each pet. If we feel an animal is suffering, the doctor's recommendation may include humane euthanasia. It is one of the saddest things we can say to a client. We don't say it to force a client to do it, but to be honest about the severity of what is going on. We want to save every animal who comes to us; that is why we are here. That is why we work nights, holidays and weekends when other locations are closed. Race has never and will never be a factor in how we treat a client or their pet. My name is Heather. I am a manager at Solano-Napa Pet Emergency Clinic and I am proud to say my origins are from El Salvador. We have a very diverse staff. We have a handful of staff members who are Hispanic, including a doctor and we are always available to speak in Spanish if that helps our clients understand what is going on better. I am very happy to hear that Silverado Vet was able to help your mom and her cat and that is all we ever want. I hope you and your family never have to go through this again and hope you can see that this is written with extreme compassion and sincerity. If you or your family ever does have an emergency and you choose to come back to us for our help, please feel free to ask for me or another Spanish-speaking employee if I am not on shift. I am more than happy to speak to your family in Spanish and properly explain everything that is going on. My staff and I wish your family the best and your kitty a smooth recovery! ~Heather"}</response>< user_id>

<Response>{'time': 1597708193045, 'text': "Dear Sally,\nThis is one of the most descriptive and accurate reviews I've seen. Thank you for the feedback!\n\nI would like to give our thoughts on a couple of important issues you raise. In human medicine we tend to have diagnostics like bloodwork done even when we know that a majority of the time it won't change what is done. It is considered necessary because as a culture we've decided that we want to avoid complications if there is any easy way (within reason) we can avoid them. If you are one of the people (or dogs) who has a critical issue found by these diagnostics, the test that is unnecessary for most becomes very necessary for you. At SPEC, we offer diagnostics that are practically meant to protect our patients, but we are open to discussing options with clients at any time. Our clients are our partners in making the decisions on the care that is provided. We welcome discussions on why we make the recommendations we do.\n\nBecause many of our patients at SPEC are nervous and don't understand what we are doing to help them, local anesthesia can have more limits than in human medicine. Sometimes it works really well (e.g. Golden Retriever with a small laceration on the leg), but there are many conditions when heavy sedation or general anesthesia are well worth doing. The consideration is not just based on how easy or hard it is to work with a given patient, but more importantly how painful or stressful the experience will be for that patient. Our veterinarians are well trained and experienced in making these judgments and if needed,  in most cases we find that anesthesia can be safely done in senior pets.\n\nThank you for the recommendations!\nDr. Shac and the Staff of SPEC"}< /Response>< user>
102078050600863619255< /user>
< pics>
None< /pics>
<review>I would have left a 3 start review but leaving 4 because my dog healed well and is doing well afterwards.
I personally had a good experience at Solano-Napa Pet Emergency. It was affordable and had the cheapest office visit $.
It was my first time ever at a E-clinic for my almost 9 year old dog who I thought had a fox-tail. I arrived around 1:30 and left the clinic around 6:30 pm so I was there for about 5 hours to be let in. Priority goes to real, life-threatening emergencies so if you're coming here from afar, expect to wait a long time.
I waited about an hour to 1.5 hours to have my dog be let in and they kept her probably for another hour to get her diagnosis. Then it probably took them 30 - 45 minutes to talk to me about treatment and payment and then another 30 minute to get the dog into a doctor for treatment (foxtail probe). They probably kept her for 10-20 minutes before giving me a call to pick her up. Once I received the call, it took about 20-30 minutes to have her back in my arms before driving off. They couldn't detect a foxtail so she was under antibiotics for about a week and afterwards has healed up very well.
This is where most people are thrown off in their reviews, its the payment part. E-clinics can be very expensive but you don't have to do all the recommended items shown in your quote. Of course, if it's life threatening, itd be different story but for my case, I was able to think, do some research my self, and decide that I didn't need to do all of the recommended things the doc suggested for a foxtail probe. The doctor suggested additional, unnecessary testing which I refused because my dog either recently had it done or had an appointment to get it done by her primary vet. Also, if you dog does not need to go under with general anesthesia, don't! Especially with senior dogs. Local anesthesia works just as well, the vets always charge more and ask you do blood work and bunch of other tests for local anesthesia because they are afraid your dog may not behave during the treatment. If you know your animals temperament and know they do fine, then ask for local anesthesia (only given your dog's circumstances). As the pet owner, you have the voice to say what would be best for your pet.
For quote, they give you a low and high quote and make you pay a deposit of the average. Then based on your treatment, you either get a refund or need to pay more. I saw more clients get a refund then pay more than the deposit. The nurse (lady) who talked me through the quote and treatment was exceptionally kind and communicative. If I had questions, she had no problem explaining or asking the doctor (back and forth). The doctor was more uncomfortable with me wanting local anesthesia probably because he doesn't want to be liable but he was still kind and understanding.
The doctors and nurses were kind and communicative. The front desk people could be a little bit more relatable since pet parents are there for emergencies so I would like to say that they be a little more kind. I understand the stress they must be under with plethora of patients but I can also understand the stress the parents must be under.
Bottom line, I had a good experience at Solano-Napa E-Clinic. They are more affordable than other E-Clinics (I called about 12+ other locations) and the staff there were overall nice and considerate. I would recommend this E-Clinic over other ones.<//review></record></dataset><record>

Barb Stocking</name>

Thank you for your compassionate and speedy care for my cat during a very trying time (Shelter in place...) I appreciate it.< /Text>

<userid>110500822194151311633</userid><Name>Wendy Hamilton</Name>< date>
1561419698780</date>
<rate>5< /rate>< Review>
I had a beautiful almost 16 year old exotic Persian...  I knew he was not well, but he continued to be somewhat social; ate and drank..I made an appointment with my regular Vet for the next day.  Five hours before is appointment, he took a very quick turn for the worse.. was barely breathing.. I scooped him up and took him to the Pet Emergency in Cordelia.  When I walked in there was a room full of dogs & cats needing help, but they could see quickly my cat was near death and took us immediately.  Being that he was almost 16, I was given the option to begin life saving procedures, but I knew it was his time, and I just did not want him to be in pain.  We decided to euthanize and give him a peaceful death.  This is something I have never experienced.  I have to say the compassion and kindness of the Doctor and the entire staff was so comforting.. I was able to hold my sweet baby until he took his last breath.  They wrapped him in a beautiful blanket so I could bury him on my property.  They also made a mold of his paw prints.  Something I look at daily.   Then to my complete surprise, I received a sympathy card in the mail about a week later. Although my story is sad.. the people at this Clinic made this difficult situation a bearable experience and I will be forever grateful to them all.</Review>

<pics>None< /pics>< resp>
{'time': 1563934182669, 'text': "I know it can be frustrating to have diagnostics run and still not confirm what the problem is. It is for us too and I know that the same thing happens in human medicine as well. But the reason we run diagnostics is because finding useful information can really help us care for our patients better than guessing. Normal or inconclusive diagnostics are helpful by themselves because they also help us know what is NOT the cause of the medical issue.\n\nI am sorry about the costs. ER clinics are more expensive than day practices just like human ER's cost more than our regular physicians. ER's have much higher staff and equipment costs; there is no way around that. If you check around our area, our emergency clinic has a cheaper exam fee than any other veterinary ER and our prices tend to be less. We keep it this way just because we know how expensive it can be for our clients. We do our part to make it as affordable as possible.\n\nI hope your pet is doing well."}</resp>

<resp>{'time': 1562802057473, 'text': "Thank you for your valuable feedback. We appreciate hearing from our clients and are grateful for difficult reviews when we've not been as good as we should be. Wait times can sometimes be longer because we don't have appointments. We have ~40 local veterinary hospitals who trust us to help their clients and patients when they are closed. We don't turn anyone away-- we are here for anyone who needs our help. But sometimes a lot of patients need our help all at once.\n\nYes, our costs are higher than a daytime veterinary practice because our overhead costs are much higher. Radiographs at our practice are almost a 1/3 of $800 (there must have been other items on the estimate you were given) and our prices are actually similar or cheaper than any other ER in our area. Our exam fee is less than any other emergency clinic around -- we purposely keep it low as possible to try to make it easier for clients to seek help. I also want to assure you your pet was examined when our staff brought your pet back to the treatment area for immediate triage. We would not have the loyalty of 40 referring veterinary clinics if we didn't operate with integrity. I am truly sorry your visit was not to your satisfaction, but I also want to assure you we will be here if you ever need us in the future."}< /resp>< GmapID>

We keep our emergency fee far below the industry standard because we want to lower the barriers to pets receiving needed care. Absolutely fair prices, especially for emergency calls! Wonderful staff who, even in the worst of times are caring and understanding when it counts. < Review>
I'm so very grateful to the Solano-Napa Pet Emergency Clinic.  Last January my cat Leo sustained a very bad bite wound on his back, probably the result of an unpleasant encounter with a raccoon.  Numerous tooth marks were clearly visible on his back, including a deep puncture wound and a lot of missing hair, in a 4" square area.  It was 8:00 pm and Leo was yowling in pain.  I knew that he needed professional care.  We called the Clinic and they told us to bring him in immediately.

He was examined, his back shaved and he was taken into surgery later that night.  The staff on duty - the vet and an assistant - were kind, very competent and reassuring.  When I picked him up the following morning, he was stitched up and in good shape.  The Clinic had even notified Leo's regular vet of his injury and had arranged for the regular vet to remove the sutures after 10 days.

Thank you, Solano-Napa Pet Emergency Clinic, for being there when Leo and I  needed after-hours help. You have my highest recommendation.< /Review>

<Date>1389288302114</Date><Review>My beloved Norman was hit by a car on 7/4/2012 in front of my parents house in Benicia - I was, of course, nearly as far from Benicia as one can be and still be in the Bay Area  - I told my dad to google emergency vets and I'd meet him there. This is the place that came up!

Norman had been hit by a truck towing a boat, he'd been pushed under the chassis and the skin from his belly and inner thigh had been, essentially, flash fried. And the tire went over his tail. We lost the tail.

Norman was diagnoised with Cancer in March of 2013 and we lost him six months later, in September, so the last year of his life was a very difficult in and out of vets and oncologists, but I always remembered and have always been thankful at the level of care he received here - his injuries were extensive and the vet said it wasn't the injuries that were life threatening, but the pain. They said if he made it though the first night, he'd be fine. To help, they set him up on a pallet in the main body of the actually clinic - right there in the middle of the room. Needless to say, he lasted the night.

Last summer, I was in Vallejo helping a friend move and my young dog, Bacon, was pulling things out of my purse - one thing was a bottle of tegretol, an anti-seziure medication. Before I knew it, she'd eaten the bottle and possibly most of the contents. We rushed to the ER and while they found nothing (I'd shoved my hand pretty far down her throat and retrieve a few myself)  it is a price beyond rubies to know there is place so close that is so well equipped to help animals.

Also, easy to find, just exit at Scandia (right?) and push back towards the hill until the road stops. Plenty of parking and one shot coffee in the lobby (which is really handy).

Five Stars.</Review>< user>

<review>I‚Äôve heard a lot of positive reviews of Haidilao so I was excited to eat here when a friend and I came in a Thursday night after a quick hike at neighboring Schabarum. We walked right in and were seated outside for the patio dining. They do offer takeout. I like the aprons they provide and the service is top-notch. They offer both hot pot and skewers, which are grilled right in your line of sight.

The food was delicious but it is pricey. The premise is that you can select however many broths you‚Äôd like ( the original mala and pork were solid choices) and can select as many toppings you‚Äôd like. The angus short rib combo comes with your standard veggies (but no enoki mushrooms) and a small portion of meat. Get some spam for your mala hot pot and some yam noodles! There was a sweet doughy bread that you dip in icing that we ordered and I had liked a lot. The lamb skewers were small but tasty. They give you generous amounts of ingredients to create your own dipping sauce. Unfortunately no dancing noodles because of covid.

They do accept credit cards and I didn‚Äôt see any bathrooms available. Parking is easy since it‚Äôs right in the Puente Hills Mall. People were smoking but at least you can sit outside. They do serve alcohol. Overall, a fun experience and I‚Äôll go back with my family next time.</review>< Pics>

Haidilao Hotpot Restaurant, located in the Puente Hills Mall in City of Industry,California,is
THE most delicious hotpot restaurant around!
The Haidilao Hotpot Restaurant in Puente Hills Mall is the newest addition to Haidilao Hotpot Restaurants.
As you walk in to the restaurant you are greeted by the friendly and courteous staff that seats you promptly.
The restaurant is brite,open and spacious and your waiter or waitress immediately greets you and answers any questions you may have regarding any of their selections.
Haidilao Hotpot features the freshest and highest quality of meats,fish,poultry and vegetables for the hotpot dishes-the selections seem endless at Haidilao and the base soup flavors are in a word-DELICIOUS!
We had the delicious Kobe beef,sirloin,scallops,a variety of the freshest and the best tasting fish as well as tofu and
vegetables.
They also have an extensive variety of ingredients at their sauce bar that is self serve
so you can add anything you'd like to for you hotpot meal!
It was a great time with friends as we all sat together and created our meal together!
The staff was very attentive and always
refilled our soup bases and were prompt with
all of the ingredients that we ordered.
We were very happy with our dinner at Haidilao Hotpot in the Puente Hills Mall.
Plenty of free parking,family,child and senior adult friendly-we had great experience at Haidilao Hotpot Restaurant and are looking forward to coming back soon!< /review>

<user>108214891915151976565</user><name>Jo Seto< /name>< date>
1575583887040<//date>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
< text>
We loved the setup of this location and loved the experience! Great the use of technology, too! They use a tablet menu for ordering and leave it at your table.  The food rolls out on a robotic cart and the staff puts it on your table.

The soup base we ordered were pork (veggies and gogi berries with light herbs) and spicy pork.  We loved both. They come and top off the soup with regular broth and I feel it dilutes the original flavor.

The MEAT was amazing.  We had the wagyu and lamb combo. It was tasty and surprisingly filling.  This is not AYCE and a bit on the higher price point. The dancing noodles look like a gimmick ($4 for a small bowl), but the noodles are legitimate good and has a good QQ texture.

The sauce bar was always clean and full!  They do a great job with maintaining the supply.  The sauce bar also has appetizers and desserts. The cold cut beef tripe in spicy oil was notably delicious; all the rest was decent at best.

There can be a wait depending on when you go. But have no fear, the waiting area outside was fully stocked with snacks, drinks, and games.<//text>

<text>Pretty good hotpot!

After being introduced to the chain back in China, this particular location does not come close to the level of service or the food buffet options.

However, when comparing to other hotpot places near LA this location is quite good in their quality and freshness of food.

If you want pretty good hotpot with quality standards, this is the place to go to. But do not expect to get wowed if you are a hot pot veteran.</text>< user_name>

< review>
Great hot pot restaurant located inside the mall. This restaurant goes above and beyond to please customers. This includes providing juice and snacks to waiting customers outside, providing a pouch to avoid dipping a phone into a hot pot, aprons, and even a hair tie to those who wear long hair in order to enjoy a meal to the full extent. We had spicy broth (medium) with butter and mushroom broth, both were excellent. Ingredients were very fresh. The source section had high quality items. I would love to visit again and try different items.</review>

<time>1597168190609< /time><Review>Horrible and disappointing experience from someone who adores HaiDiLao Hotpot from Asia. I traveled to Singapore over the summer and had my first experience with HaiDiLao there.  It was so different.

As you wait for a table outside the restaurant, customers are given free icecream, Japanese rice snacks, popcorn, green tea, fruit drinks, manicures and pedicures. Once you are seated, servers give you hot towels and aprons and you are open to get as much as you want from a free sauce and appetizer bar. Everything is ordered from an ipad. The actual hot pot which held the soup is flush with the table, allowing for easy access to the broth. When the vegetables and meats were served, they were placed on a cart so that your table is not cluttered. When the meal is over, you can then go over to the fridge and get as many desserts and you'd like. Soy milk and traditional Chinese desserts.

Let me tell you.. that really was an experience.

I went to this HaiDiLao excited to have this same experience but in the states. I reserved a table for 4 and we drove to the location excited for a meal. The experience was completely different.

We were seated at a tiny table with a cheap propane burner. Everything is still ordered from an ipad. The pot comes out and it's the cheap pot you find at any other hot pot place. They don't even have the most basics of broths... Chicken broth. No towels or aprons for the meal. No free appetizers. When asked what sauces we wanted, the server brought out some for us.. we expected them to be free. I mean, sauces are basically necessary for hotpot enjoyment. But no. They charged us $1 for each person for sauces. Absolutely ridiculous. Vegetables and meats were of high quality, but that was the only positive. Furthermore, they were stacked on our table and made it extremely cluttered. Unlike the one in Asia, the desserts were expensive and not free. The prices for meats and vegetables were the same as they were in Singapore, but after accounting for exchange, that meant that the Singapore meal was cheaper.

We left with a sour taste in our mouth. This experience was not unlike any other buffet hotpot location, except it wasn't a buffet and everything was charged like microtransactions in a game.

We will never ever go back, or reccomend this place to anyone.

While I understand that COVID impacted some things such as paper plates instead of regular dishes, those things were not considered in this review. If they were, I would rate this place at 0 stars. The differences are staggering enough to warrant a 1 star review.<//Review>< Pics>

<Name>5 minutes alone< /Name>< Text>
It is pretty good restaurant that opened in the La Puente Mall. It is pretty good but it takes the liquid time to boil but it is clean and not like those KBBQ. So the way it works; you order your soup that is either spicy or normal that has different flavors, then you order raw meat, vegetables, and other stuff. They bring the soup and they put it on a oven where it boils it. As it boils, you place the meat and vegetables inside and it will start to cook it. <rating>2</rating>< pics>
None<//pics>
< Review>
Domino's has always been my favorite chain pizza place. Unfortunately between my terrible experience with this Domino's and their apathy towards it, and Papa John's being, well, Papa John's, my pizza options are becoming extremely limited.

I love pizza crust. I'm not the type to just toss it away. This may have been the first time I've thrown away my crust since I was 8 years old. Maybe it was a bad batch, maybe they were just having a bad day, but it tasted like cardboard. The dry, fibrous bread they used might have been passable if they hadn't skimped so much on sauce and cheese. They went fairly light on toppings as well.

Delivery took about 20 minutes longer than approximated. That happens, I get it. Just strange when I get a message that the pizza left the store 30 minutes ago, I live 10 minutes away, and I still had to wait about 15 minutes. Pizza was lukewarm when it arrived. Delivery driver was nice enough at least (the reason I gave 2 and not 1 star).

The pizza was so underwhelming and off that I felt the need to actually send my response to Domino's HQ, just in case their quality control has gone to pot, or to at least make the store aware of what caliber pizza they're sending out. Domino's HQ sent me a very friendly message back, letting me know that the store would be in touch to correct the situation. That never actually happened, which is why I'm leaving this review to prevent more catastrophic pizza failures from getting to the google-savvy pizza-loving local population.

Overall, it may be a blessing in disguise, this cheese-encrusted disappointment. My last blood tests showed my cholesterol was a bit elevated, so at least I won't have this Domino's as a temptation any more. Thanks for watching out for my lipid profile Domino's!</Review>

< Text>
At&t is able to engage in implicit theft via their associated business, directvnow:

If I could give 0 stars, I would. I opened a phone service with at&t back in March 2018, and I unknowingly got some kind of "free trial" with directvnow with it. I had no idea this was signed up under my name, that my bank information was given over to directvnow, and that I would be charged $35 - $40 every month after. I never used this service-- I never even knew how to while I had this account.

It was only after I closed my at&t account (for unrelated reasons) that I finally realized the directvnow charge was actually instigated by at&t. Somehow directvnow cannot locate any account with my information because is now closed-- and yet THEY STILL HAVE MY BANK INFORMATION and I'm STILL BEING CHARGED EVERY MONTH.

After changing my bank card three times-- STILL being charged from directvnow-- I actually have to close my bank account essentially because of unagreed terms and withheld explicit information on the part of at&t.

Essentially, at&t / directvnow stole from me, via bureaucratic technicalities. Seriously, how do you have my bank information for a monthly bill, and yet you cannot locate my account to cancel?

If you are with at&t or signing up, I strongly advise you look at their fine print agreements and your information they share with directvnow. Otherwise you may find yourself under theft every month, and having to close your bank account.</Text>
